    "content": "Lawmakers and military officials in Somalia have expressed grave concern over reports that the Trump administration is planning to withdraw nearly all U.S. troops from the country. The proposed drawdown, which would remove approximately 700 U.S. military personnel currently engaged in training and counterterrorism missions, is seen as a potential disaster for Somalia's fragile security situation.\n\nSenator Ahmd Hashi, secretary of Somalia’s Upper House Committee on defense, described the proposal as the United States 'turning its back on Somalis at a critical time.' He emphasized that the country is heading toward parliamentary elections in late December 2020, followed by presidential elections in February 2021, and that the terrorist threat from al-Shabab remains significant. Hashi warned that a U.S. withdrawal would be a 'moral boost for terrorists' and a 'terrible blow to the Somali Army.'\n\nThe U.S. forces have been pivotal in supporting the Somali military, particularly the elite Danab commando unit. They have provided critical logistics and operational support, helping the unit grow stronger. A withdrawal, Hashi argued, would reverse these gains and undermine the fight against terrorism. The New York Times report indicated that Trump also plans sharp troop reductions in Afghanistan and Iraq, part of a broader shift in U.S. military posture.",
